# OneNote MCP Server — environment example
# Copy to .env and fill in values.

# --- Transport ---
# PORT=8000
# HOST=0.0.0.0

# --- Auth Mode (oauth2 | oauth2_proxy | az_cli) ---
#
#  oauth2       : Single app registration (AzureProvider + built-in OBO).
#                 Requires AZURE_CLIENT_ID, AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET, AZURE_TENANT_ID.
#                 Needs admin consent in enterprise tenants.
#
#  oauth2_proxy : Two app registrations — client (public, admin-approved) + server.
#                 Avoids admin consent issues when App B is already approved.
#                 Requires AZURE_CLIENT_ID (App B), AZURE_SERVER_CLIENT_ID,
#                 AZURE_SERVER_CLIENT_SECRET, AZURE_TENANT_ID.
#
#  az_cli       : No MCP-level auth; Graph token from Azure CLI.
#                 Just run 'az login' first. No env vars needed beyond transport.
#
AUTH_MODE=oauth2

# ==========================================================================
# oauth2 mode — single app registration
# ==========================================================================
# Create an App Registration in Azure Portal:
#   1. "Expose an API" → add scope "mcp-access", set token version to 2
#   2. "Authentication" → add redirect URI: http://localhost:8000/auth/callback
#   3. "Certificates & secrets" → create a client secret
#   4. "API permissions" → add delegated: Notes.Read, Notes.Read.All, User.Read, Group.Read.All
#      → Grant admin consent
#   5. "Authentication" → Allow public client flows = Yes
#
# AZURE_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id
# AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET=your-client-secret
# AZURE_TENANT_ID=your-tenant-id
# MCP_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000

# ==========================================================================
# oauth2_proxy mode — two app registrations (client + server)
# ==========================================================================
# Uses AzureOAuthProxy: MCP clients send resource=http://.../mcp (RFC 8707); that
# parameter is NOT forwarded to Entra /authorize to avoid AADSTS9010010 (resource
# vs scope mismatch).
#
# App B (client), approved by admin for delegated access to App A:
#   - Redirect URI (Web): {MCP_BASE_URL}/auth/callback  (e.g. http://localhost:8000/auth/callback)
#   - "API permissions" → delegated: api://<App A>/mcp-access → admin consent
#   - If App B is a Web app (typical): Certificates & secrets → client secret → set AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET
#     (token exchange requires it; else AADSTS7000218)
#   - If App B is a true public client only: "Allow public client flows" = Yes and omit AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET
#
# App A (server) — exposes scope + has Graph permissions:
#   - "Expose an API" → add scope "mcp-access", set token version to 2
#   - "Certificates & secrets" → create a client secret (for OBO)
#   - "API permissions" → add delegated: Notes.Read, Notes.Read.All, User.Read, Group.Read.All
#      → Grant admin consent
#
# AZURE_CLIENT_ID=app-b-client-id
# AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET=app-b-client-secret
# AZURE_SERVER_CLIENT_ID=app-a-server-client-id
# AZURE_SERVER_CLIENT_SECRET=app-a-server-secret-for-obo
# AZURE_TENANT_ID=your-tenant-id
# MCP_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000
# Optional: if App A "Application ID URI" is not api://<AZURE_SERVER_CLIENT_ID>, set it for JWT aud check:
# AZURE_SERVER_AUDIENCE=api://your-custom-uri

# ==========================================================================
# az_cli mode — no extra env vars needed
# ==========================================================================
# Just run:
#   az login
#   az account set --subscription <your-subscription>   (if needed)
